abstract: NEWARK, N.J., July 31 -- A storm of unusual violence struck this city this morning, doing much damage. abstract: WASHINGTON, July 31 -- At the opening of business at the United States Treasury this morning it had in its possession the largest fund of gold held by any nation in the world and the greatest ever possessed by this Government. At 9 o'clock the fund amounted to $504,354,297. This involves an increase during the past month of nearly $10,000,000 and an increase of $74,422,422 over the figures of the corresponding date of last year.

abstract: The Hamburg-American liner Deutschland arrived in New York yesterday morning, having broken two more records on the westward, run. She made a new record for a day's run, and also established a new one for the average number of knots logged during the passage. Six hundred and one knots was the distance traversed by the great liner Tuesday, which beats the best previous record, which she also holds, by seventeen knots.

abstract: BOSTON, Aug. 1 -- The market had another lifeless and uninteresting day of it. There were long intervals of almost complete stagnation, and for one period of nearly an hour the aggregate transactions amounted to less than 300 shares. abstract: BERLIN, Aug. 3. -- The Tariff bill continues to be discussed in a lively manner. It is generally recognized that much depends upon the attitude of the South German Cabinets, and, during the last few days the semi-official utterances there have taken the cue of The North German Gazette, that the bill is only tentative. But it is regarded as certain that South German officials desire many changes.

abstract: WITHIN the last fortnight the section of Broadway running through Manhattan Valley, from One Hundred and Twenty-fifth to One Hundred and Thirty-fifth Street, has begun to be specked with two parallel rows of square holes through the pavement. abstract: About 480 cyclists started in the annual "veterans," century run over the Long Island roads yesterday morning, and about 300 of them managed to finish after an exhausting ride through the rain and over muddy roads. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Aug. 5 -- A terrific explosion in a block of six buildings on Locust Street above Tenth to-night completely wrecked five of the structures and caused the death of two persons. Over fifty others were more or less seriously injured. It is estimated that at least thirty-five persons were in the five buildings when the explosion occurred, and the exact number of dead is not known.

abstract: Much more activity appeared on the curb yesterday than on any day since the beginning of last week. Prices, however, were generally weak, and in most of the active issues quotations at the close were considerably below those of Saturday. The greater activity, accompanied by rather sharp declines, suggested that the general outlook induced many to liquidate their holdings in some of the more active issues notably the Can stocks and the Tobacco bonds.

abstract: Herman Colell, wholesale dealer in tobacco at 10 Chatham Square, has filed a petition in bankruptcy, with liabilities $94,474, and assets $50,072. Of the liabilities $75,204 are secured, $9,269 unsecured, and $10,000 accommodation paper. The assets consist of real estate, 1,023 Third Avenue, Brooklyn, $7,000, mortgaged for $8,500; accounts, $39,725; stock on hand, $8,000; equity in tobacco pledged unknown; fixtures, $100; shares of stock of the Bedell Leaf Tobacco Company, $4,000; cash. $247.

abstract: PITTSBURG, Aug. 7. -- In the big stee strike honors are easy in this section to-night. abstract: PITTSBURG, Aug. 11. -- The iron masters are to-night claiming victory in the great steel strike. abstract: The troubles of the Beth Eden Baptist Church in Belmont, Borough of the Bronx, were settled yesterday. The church, up to a few months ago, was Baptist. Now it is both Baptist and Presbyterian. The Baptists were unable to pay off a mortgage of $1,500 held by Charles A. Tatum, and he was forced to foreclose.

abstract: Total transactions on the Stock Exchange list reached barely to figures which but a little while ago were regarded as ordinary totals for a day. abstract: STROUDSBURG, Penn., Aug. 15. -- Ex-Judge John B. Storm died to-day in his rooms in the Burnett House after a long illness. He was one of the leading Democrats in Eastern Pennsylvania, and served four terms in Congress. After the death of Judge Drehr, in 1894, he was appointed a Judge in the Monroe-Carbon district.

abstract: NEWPORT, R.I., Aug. 15. -- With the exception of one match, the National tennis tournament has gone through the second round. One step more brings it to the semifinals. The Davis-Wright match, which is a day behind, will be played to-morrow. The winner will play Hobart on Saturday. The other third round match will be played to-morrow, the pairings being Ware and Leonard, W.A. Larned and E.P. Larned, Little and Clothier.

abstract: ITHACA, N.Y., Aug. 15. -- The Groton Bridge Company of Groton, which was recently absorbed by the big United States Steel Corporation, posted a notice to-day to the effect that the mills will be closed down indefinitely Saturday night. abstract: NEWPORT, R.I., Aug. 15. -- The first polo match for the Westchester Club Cup was played this afternoon between the Philadelphia Freebooters and the Myopias, the former winning -- 8 3/4 to 8. The fog hung heavy on the polo field, making it difficult at times to follow the players. The dampness made the ground holding, however, and the ball, did not bound so badly as in the other matches this season.

abstract: AUGUST is the month of highest mortality among city children. The heat gradually weakens the delicate infantile constitutions, and toward the end of August, sometimes even at the beginning of September, the death record of the little victims reaches its maximum. Adults as a rule have grown accustomed to the hot weather by this time, and bear very well temperatures that would have seemed insupportable at the beginning of the Summer.

abstract: LEXINGTON, Ky., Aug. 17. -- This was the last day of the Elks' fair and races. abstract: The Freneh liner La Gascogne steamed into port yesterday, and reported that she had encountered very stormy weather. For four days the great liner had been compelled to contend against the fury of the wind and rain. Though she was tossed about considerably, much to the discomfort of her passengers; she nevertheless came into port undamaged, not so much as a rail being bent by the heavy seas.

abstract: PARIS, Aug. 18 -- The International bicycle race from Paris to Brest and return, a distance of 750 miles, was finished to-day and was won by Garin, who reaching the finishing point in the Paris Velodrome at 9:04 A.M., having covered the entire course it 52 hours and 11 minutes. abstract: PITTSBURG, Penn., Aug. 18 -- There is talk to-night of the probable extension of the strike to other trades. The structural iron workers and bricklayers are becoming directly interested through the question of handling material made by the United States Steel Corporation. abstract: CHICAGO, Aug. 24 -- Telamon easily won the Excelsior Stakes at Hawthorne this afternoon, beating a good field with little effort. Five horses started in the race, a mile and an eighth, with $2,000 added. Telamon opened at 6 to 5 and went up to 2 to 1. At the far turn the field was in a bunch, but on the stretch Telamon swung into the lead.

abstract: WORCESTER, Mass., Aug. 28. -- John A. Nelson defeated William C. Stinson at the Coliseum to-night by two-thirds of a lap in a twenty-mile motor-paced race. abstract: WASHINGTON, Aug. 29. -- According to a bulletin issued by the Census Bureau to-day, there are slightly more females than males in the State of New York. The percentage is 60.3 to 49.7. Out of a total population of 7,268,894, there are 3,614,780 males and 3,654,114 females. Of the total population of the State 1,900,425, or 26.1 per cent., are foreign-born, and 112,013, or 1.5 per cent., are colored.
